borhood’s fight to erase the stigma of devastation. Frederick F. Wherry shows how, in the predominantly Latino neighborhood of Centro de Oro, entrepreneurs and community leaders forged connections between local businesses and cultural institutions to rebrand a place once nicknamed the Badlands. Artists and performers negotiated with government organizations and national foundations, Wherry reveals, and took to local galleries, stages, storefronts, and street parades in a concerted, canny effort to reanimate the spirit of their neighborhood. Complicating our notions of neighborhood change by exploring the ways the process is driven by local residents, The Philadelphia Barrio presents a nuanced look at how city dwellers can make commercial interests serve the local culture, rather than exploit it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommunity arts projectsxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aCommunity arts projectszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aCommunity developmentxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aCommunity developmentzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aHispanic American neighborhoodsxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aHispanic American neighborhoodszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aArbor, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226894461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226894461.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles